               <msContents>
                  <msItem class="#computistica" n="1" xml:id="MS_Douce_71-item1">
                     <title key="work_10175" type="desc">Folding concertina almanac</title>
                     <note>Recto (to be
                        folded inwards): (A) 12 month calendar, each month occupying two squares of parchment, and showing (1) saints' days, with saints portrayed as emblems or busts (2) dominical letters (3) two sets of golden numbers (represented using pentadic ('runic' or 'disguised Roman') numerals), one red and one blank, for the ecclesiastical new moon and the real new moon. (B) Six notable dates: years from the creation of the world, the age of Adam, the age of Eve, the time Adam was in Purgatory ('Adam fuit in inferno'), years from the Flood, and years from the Incarnation (1432). The years are given both in roman numerals and in symbolic form (thousands in black,
                        hundreds, tens, and single years in red.)</note>
                     <note>Verso: images of the occupations of the months, each accompanied by a circular diagram with red and black lines indicating the number of daylight and night-time
                        hours during the month.</note>
                     <note>The design is almost identical to later xylographic almanacs such as <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/a196b40f-1c6c-4b92-a51c-129a349efb24/">Douce A 632*</ref>, for which see Bod-Inc XYL-2.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                    
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
