                  </origin>
                  <provenance>Part of a "close group" of five manuscripts which Gumbert attributed to "the same workshop, certainly in the diocese of Utrecht (by the sanctoral) and possibly in the town of Utrect itself" (J. P. Gumbert, <title>Bat books : a catalogue of folded manuscripts containing almanacs or other texts</title> (2016), pp. 214-215)</provenance>
                  <provenance> At fol. 1 is a letter from Daines Barrington, dated Feb. 18, 1778, stating that the almanac was found at Lynn in Norfolk, and was at the time of writing in the possession of <persName role="fmo" key="person_12179247">Ashton Lever, esq.</persName>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <persName role="fmo" key="person_3982">Henry Jadis</persName>: sold at Evans, 25 Jan. 1830, lot 735, for £1 14s; bought by Thorpe (<title>Douce Legacy</title>, no. 176). Bought from Thorpe for £3 13s. 6d. in April 1830 by:</provenance>
                  <provenance notAfter="1834" notBefore="1757" resp="#MMM">
                     <persName key="person_69848690" role="fmo">Francis Douce, 1757–1834</persName>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition resp="#MMM" when="1834">Bequeathed to the Bodleian in 1834</acquisition>
               </history>
